{
  "doc_id": "52133",
  "text": "Acute pancreatitis is an inflammatory disease of the pancreas caused by the production and release of various inflammatory cytokines. Approximately 20% of patients with acute pancreatitis develop severe acute pancreatitis (SAP) [CITATION_1] , which is a common and potentially fatal disease and is characterized by a mortality risk of 10%-30% and various complications [CITATION_2] . In the early stage of SAP, the cause of mortality is closely associated with single or multiple organ complications such as lung injury and intestine barrier functional disturbance [CITATION_3] . In particular, intestinal injury is one of the most frequent complications of this severe disease, and extensive research demonstrates that it contributes significantly to high morbidity and mortality [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
